Iteration with purrr

Excellent resources

  • Jenny Bryan’s webinar: Thinking inside the box: you can do that inside a data frame?!
  • Jenny Bryan’s purrr tutorial

Syntax

purrr::map(.x, .f, ...)

For each element of .x, do function .f with ... parameters.

Basic example

Now that we have a general idea of what’s going on, how do we use it in practice? Let’s play with the starwars dataset:

Let’s say we want to write a sentence that describes how tall each character is…

starwars %>% 
    select(name, hair_color) %>% 
    mutate(sentence = paste("This character has", hair_color, "hair"))
## # A tibble: 87 x 3

##  6 Owen Lars          brown, grey   This character has brown, grey hair

##  9 Biggs Darklighter  black         This character has black hair

Great! Works like a charm. But notice that some of the characters have NA’s for hair color because they don’t have any hair. Let’s write a function to accoutn for that:

hair_sentence <- function(hair_color) {
    if(is.na(hair_color)){
        return(paste("This character has no hair."))
    }
    
    return(paste("This character has", hair_color, "hair"))
}

We should be able to use this function the way we used paste earlier…

starwars %>% 
    select(name, hair_color) %>% 
    mutate(sentence = hair_sentence(hair_color))
## Warning in if (is.na(hair_color)) {: the condition has length > 1 and only
## the first element will be used
## # A tibble: 87 x 3
##    name               hair_color    sentence                             
##    <chr>              <chr>         <chr>                                
##  1 Luke Skywalker     blond         This character has blond hair        
##  2 C-3PO              <NA>          This character has NA hair           
##  3 R2-D2              <NA>          This character has NA hair           
##  4 Darth Vader        none          This character has none hair         
##  5 Leia Organa        brown         This character has brown hair        
##  6 Owen Lars          brown, grey   This character has brown, grey hair  
##  7 Beru Whitesun lars brown         This character has brown hair        
##  8 R5-D4              <NA>          This character has NA hair           
##  9 Biggs Darklighter  black         This character has black hair        
## 10 Obi-Wan Kenobi     auburn, white This character has auburn, white hair
## # ... with 77 more rows

Alas, no! Something weird happened. The sentences for characters without hair didn’t change.

This is because the function wasn’t properly vectorized, which means that you can do something to an entire vector of values at the same time.

One way to deal with this problem is to use the map function. We can take the hair_color vector and apply the hair_sentence function to each of its elements:

starwars %>% 
    select(name, hair_color) %>% 
    mutate(sentence = map(hair_color, hair_sentence))
## # A tibble: 87 x 3
##    name               hair_color    sentence 
##    <chr>              <chr>         <list>   
##  1 Luke Skywalker     blond         <chr [1]>
##  2 C-3PO              <NA>          <chr [1]>
##  3 R2-D2              <NA>          <chr [1]>
##  4 Darth Vader        none          <chr [1]>
##  5 Leia Organa        brown         <chr [1]>
##  6 Owen Lars          brown, grey   <chr [1]>
##  7 Beru Whitesun lars brown         <chr [1]>
##  8 R5-D4              <NA>          <chr [1]>
##  9 Biggs Darklighter  black         <chr [1]>
## 10 Obi-Wan Kenobi     auburn, white <chr [1]>
## # ... with 77 more rows

Since we didn’t define an output type, it returns a list of character vectors. This is more or less what lapply does.

If you know the type of your output, you can also specify it directly:

starwars %>% 
    select(name, hair_color) %>% 
    mutate(sentence = map_chr(hair_color, hair_sentence))
## # A tibble: 87 x 3
##    name               hair_color    sentence

##  3 R2-D2              <NA>          This character has no hair.          
##  4 Darth Vader        none          This character has none hair         
##  5 Leia Organa        brown         This character has brown hair        
##  6 Owen Lars          brown, grey   This character has brown, grey hair  
##  7 Beru Whitesun lars brown         This character has brown hair

Mapping with parameters

Now let’s say you want to add a parameter to your function to capitalize the sentence for characters without hair.

hair_sentence <- function(hair_color, caps = FALSE) {
    if(is.na(hair_color)){
        no_hair <- paste("This character has no hair.")
        if(caps == TRUE){
            no_hair <- toupper(no_hair)
        }
        return(no_hair)
    }
    
    return(paste("This character has", hair_color, "hair"))
}

If we don’t supply a parameter, the function will just use the defaults. If we do want to use caps = TRUE we can do it in two ways:

  1. Supply the parameter as the 3rd argument in the map function.
starwars %>% 
    select(name, hair_color) %>% 
    mutate(sentence = map_chr(hair_color, hair_sentence, caps = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 87 x 3
##    name               hair_color    sentence                             
##    <chr>              <chr>         <chr>                                
##  1 Luke Skywalker     blond         This character has blond hair        
##  2 C-3PO              <NA>          THIS CHARACTER HAS NO HAIR.          
##  3 R2-D2              <NA>          THIS CHARACTER HAS NO HAIR.          
##  4 Darth Vader        none          This character has none hair         
##  5 Leia Organa        brown         This character has brown hair        
##  6 Owen Lars          brown, grey   This character has brown, grey hair  
##  7 Beru Whitesun lars brown         This character has brown hair        
##  8 R5-D4              <NA>          THIS CHARACTER HAS NO HAIR.          
##  9 Biggs Darklighter  black         This character has black hair        
## 10 Obi-Wan Kenobi     auburn, white This character has auburn, white hair
## # ... with 77 more rows
  1. Define all parameters for the function explicitly using ~ to represent a function and .x to represent each element of hair_color.
starwars %>% 
    select(name, hair_color) %>% 
    mutate(sentence = map_chr(hair_color, 
                              ~hair_sentence(.x, caps = TRUE)))
## # A tibble: 87 x 3
##    name               hair_color    sentence                             
##    <chr>              <chr>         <chr>                                
##  1 Luke Skywalker     blond         This character has blond hair        
##  2 C-3PO              <NA>          THIS CHARACTER HAS NO HAIR.          
##  3 R2-D2              <NA>          THIS CHARACTER HAS NO HAIR.          
##  4 Darth Vader        none          This character has none hair         
##  5 Leia Organa        brown         This character has brown hair        
##  6 Owen Lars          brown, grey   This character has brown, grey hair  
##  7 Beru Whitesun lars brown         This character has brown hair        
##  8 R5-D4              <NA>          THIS CHARACTER HAS NO HAIR.          
##  9 Biggs Darklighter  black         This character has black hair        
## 10 Obi-Wan Kenobi     auburn, white This character has auburn, white hair
## # ... with 77 more rows

Doing it this way looks weird at first, but it gives you more flexibility.

For example, you can reorder the parameters and get the same result, since you’re defining the parameters explicitly.

Try it yourself: if you wanted to write a sentence about each character’s eye color, how would you do it? If their eyecolor is unknown, write a different sentence.
